## Abstract

Early detection of patient deterioration in hospital settings remains a critical challenge, with existing early warning systems suffering from high false-positive rates, poor explainability, and static prediction horizons. We present **T-SHAP-EWS** (Temporal-SHAP Early Warning System), a novel framework that combines gradient-boosted decision trees with a time-aware extension of SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) to predict clinical deterioration 4-6 hours before onset. Our key contributions are: (1) a **Temporal-SHAP** algorithm that provides time-resolved feature attributions showing *when* and *why* each vital sign became predictive, (2) a **multi-horizon prediction architecture** that simultaneously forecasts deterioration risk at 2, 4, and 6-hour windows with calibrated confidence intervals, and (3) a **physiological plausibility scoring** mechanism that filters clinically implausible explanations. Evaluated on the MIMIC-IV dataset (n=53,150 ICU stays), T-SHAP-EWS achieves an AUROC of 0.891 (95% CI: 0.885-0.897) for 4-hour sepsis prediction and 0.923 (95% CI: 0.916-0.930) for cardiac arrest, outperforming the Modified Early Warning Score (MEWS), NEWS-2, and standard XGBoost baselines. Critically, a clinician evaluation study (n=24 ICU nurses and physicians) demonstrates that Temporal-SHAP explanations improve appropriate clinical response rates by 34% compared to risk-score-only alerts and 18% compared to standard SHAP, while reducing alert fatigue by 28%. Our framework is designed for real-world deployment via HL7 FHIR streaming integration and is released as open-source software.

**Keywords:** clinical deterioration, explainable artificial intelligence, early warning systems, SHAP, time-series, critical care, sepsis prediction

