## 2. Related Work

### 2.1 Traditional Early Warning Scores

The NEWS-2 (Royal College of Physicians, 2017) [3] aggregates six physiological parameters into a composite score triggering graded clinical responses. While widely adopted, meta-analyses report AUROC values of 0.65-0.76 for predicting cardiac arrest within 24 hours [9]. The MEWS [4] and qSOFA [10] follow similar approaches with known sensitivity limitations.

### 2.2 Machine Learning for Clinical Deterioration

Rajkomar et al. (2018) demonstrated deep learning models achieving AUROC >0.90 for in-hospital mortality prediction using EHR data [6]. The MIMIC-III dataset [11] has enabled numerous studies, with Harutyunyan et al. (2019) establishing benchmarks for four clinical prediction tasks [12]. Gradient-boosted methods (XGBoost, LightGBM) have shown competitive or superior performance to deep learning for tabular clinical data [13,14], while being more interpretable and requiring less data.

### 2.3 Sepsis-Specific Prediction

The 2019 PhysioNet Computing in Cardiology Challenge focused on early sepsis prediction [15], spurring significant research. Reyna et al. (2020) proposed a utility-based evaluation metric [16]. Notably, Moor et al. (2021) demonstrated that temporal convolutional networks could predict sepsis 6 hours in advance [17]. However, none of these approaches addressed explainability in a temporally-aware manner.

### 2.4 Explainable AI in Healthcare

SHAP (Lundberg & Lee, 2017) [18] and LIME (Ribeiro et al., 2016) [19] are the predominant post-hoc explanation methods. TreeSHAP [20] enables exact SHAP computation for tree-based models. Recent work has applied SHAP to clinical models [21,22], but these applications treat time-series features as independent static inputs, losing temporal context. TimeSHAP (Bento et al., 2021) [23] proposed temporal extensions for recurrent models, but was limited to RNN architectures and did not address physiological plausibility.

### 2.5 Patent and Commercial Landscape

Several patents exist in this space:
- **US Patent 10,818,395 (Dascena):** Machine learning-based sepsis prediction using InSight algorithm
- **US Patent 11,101,024 (Philips):** Patient deterioration prediction using sequential pattern mining
- **US Patent App. 2021/0118559 (Epic):** Clinical decision support with predictive models
- **US Patent 10,956,839 (GE Healthcare):** Real-time patient monitoring with ML-based deterioration scores

**Key differentiator from existing IP:** No existing patent claims the combination of (a) temporal SHAP explanations, (b) physiological plausibility constraints on explanations, and (c) multi-horizon calibrated predictions. Our approach is method-novel in the explanation layer rather than the prediction layer, which is the primary basis for novelty.

